04577nam a22006975i 9781487576103DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191982onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875761037 a10.3138/97814875761032doi  a(DE-B1597)536827  a(OCoLC)1129173082  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR2342.A6bL56 1982eb 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a823/.32221 aLindheim, Nancy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Structures of Sidney's Arcadia /cNancy Lindheim. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1982  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tONE. Introduction -- tTWO. Rhetorical Structure: The Topical Tradition -- tTHREE. Rhetorical Explorations: Two Topoi -- tFOUR. Tonal Structure -- tFIVE. Narrative Structure : Retrospective History -- tSIX. Narrative Explorations: Scope -- tSEVEN. Narrative Structure: Episodes and Fable -- tEIGHT. Conclusion -- tA. In medias res Construction -- tB. Tables of Relationships -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe argument of this study is that the Arcadia, like the High Renaissance painting analysed by Heinrich Wolfflin, is characterized by what may be called 'multiple unity.' The complexity of its organization, whether examined rhetorically in terms of language and thought or tonally through its sequence of events, or narratively through the relation of episode to main plot, is an expression of Sidney's need to control and arrange experience for aesthetic and moral purposes without giving up his perception of its chaos or unmanageability. The nature of Sidney's complex vision, in spite of the apparently pastoral title of Arcadia, is not pastoral but epic. Like much important Renaissance writing, the work is a paedeia, an education of princes, in which the narrative seeks what Sidney considered the paramount object of learning: 'the knowledge of a man's self, in the ethnic and politic consideration.' Professor Lindheim finds that the key to the greater stylistic and narrative complexity of the revised Arcadia lies in the larger and deeper reading of experience that it offers. The New Arcadia is not merely the Old Arcadia heavily ornamented and reassembled in quaint ways, but a radically receonceived work, a re-vision as well as a revision of the earlier version. The radical (root, upwards from the very foundation) coherence of the work is here explored by tracing its rhetoric to an inherent rhetoricism and by abalysing its style stylistically. The Arcadia is a masterpiece of Elizabethan literature because of this integrity: because Sidney's technique, whether stylistic, rhetorical, or narrative, has a direct bearing on his humanist understanding of experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArcadia in literature. 0aCountry life in literature. 0aPastoral literature, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aRhetoric, Renaissance. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757610340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487576103423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487576103.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK